subsection.p:
So the form
ax^2+2bxy+cy^2
corresponds to the matrix

  \boxed{
  \begin{pmatrix}
  a&b\\
  b&c
  \end{pmatrix}.
  }

For any square matrix A,

  \boxed{
  \mathbf x^T A\mathbf x
  =
  \mathbf x^T\left(\frac{A+A^T}{2}\right)\mathbf x.
  }

A quadratic form is positive definite if

  \boxed{
  q(\mathbf x)\gt 0
  \quad\text{for every }\mathbf x\ne\mathbf 0.
  }

A symmetric matrix A is positive definite if

  \boxed{
  \mathbf x^T A\mathbf x\gt 0
  \quad\text{for every }\mathbf x\ne\mathbf 0.
  }

A quadratic form is negative definite if

  \boxed{
  q(\mathbf x)\lt 0
  \quad\text{for every }\mathbf x\ne\mathbf 0.
  }


  \boxed{
  q(\mathbf u)\gt 0
  \quad\text{and}\quad
  q(\mathbf v)\lt 0
  }

for some vectors \mathbf u,\mathbf v.

Positive semidefinite:

  \boxed{
  q(\mathbf x)\ge0
  \quad\text{for every }\mathbf x.
  }

Negative semidefinite:

  \boxed{
  q(\mathbf x)\le0
  \quad\text{for every }\mathbf x.
  }

Let
A= \begin{pmatrix} a&b\\ b&c \end{pmatrix}
and D=\det A=ac-b^2.

If A is symmetric, then
\boxed{A=QDQ^T,}
where Q is orthogonal and D is diagonal.

For a function f(x,y), the Hessian matrix is

  \boxed{
  H_f=
  \begin{pmatrix}
  f_{xx} & f_{xy}\\
  f_{yx} & f_{yy}
  \end{pmatrix}.
  }

Let

  \boxed{
  D=f_{xx}(a,b)f_{yy}(a,b)-f_{xy}(a,b)^2.
  }
